Parents may pick up meals for any child ages 0 to 18 years old, as long as one child is a registered student at ECESD. Wednesdays will be for any member of the community ages 0 to 18 years old. Parents can find current information on our website.

The El Centro Elementary School District is proud to have distributed 885,084 meals during our community feeding program. The last day of community feeding was Monday, August 17th.

Starting August 24th, we will be serving students of our District. Parents are requested to register their students at the following link: https://bit.ly/ECESD-Meals. Parents will receive a confirmation email, that will provide information on how to pick-up their child’s meal card and weekly meals. Please allow 48 hours to receive the confirmation email. We encourage parents to register as soon as possible to ensure proper planning and distribution. More information can be found on our website: www.ecesd.org.

Mensaje del Superintendente LeDoux: Hoy, el gobernador ha anunciado que los distritos escolares ubicados en los condados que están en la lista de vigilancia estatal COVID-19 comenzarán el año con estudiantes que aprenden solo en línea. Nuestras escuelas permanecerán cerradas hasta que el condado de Imperial no esté en la lista de vigilancia estatal por 14 días consecutivos. Si bien nuestros estudiantes no podrán asistir a sus escuelas locales, estamos trabajando arduamente para garantizar que nuestro programa de aprendizaje a distancia sea dinámico, significativo e impactante.
Vuelva a consultar aquí y en nuestra página web del distrito en www.ecesd.org para obtener actualizaciones. A continuación, puede leer la declaración conjunta del Dr. Finnell y el Dr. Munday escrita en nombre de todos los superintendentes en el Condado de Imperial.
Gracias.

Message from Superintendent LeDoux: Today, the governor has announced that school districts located in counties that are on the State COVID-19 watch list will begin the year with students learning online only. Our school sites will remain closed until Imperial County is not on the state watch list for 14 consecutive days. While our students will not be able to be at their local schools, we are working hard to ensure that our distance learning program will be dynamic, meaningful and impactful.

Please check back here and on our District webpage at www.ecesd.org for updates. Below, you can read the joint statement by Dr. Finnell and Dr. Munday written on behalf of all superintendents in Imperial County.

Thank you.

post_text:
HELPING OUR NEIGHBORS
The incredible devastation of the recent fires in Niland has left our Valley with a heavy heart. Numerous homes were lost and hundreds of residents have been displaced. To help our neighbors to the north, ECESD has transferred several thousand pounds of food to the Calipatria Unified School District to help feed the community during this time of crisis. As you can see in the pictures, the Child Nutrition Team, lead by Assistant Superintendent Kristy Curry and Director Molly Diaz, along with our incredible Warehouse Employees and Delivery drivers, delivered over 250 cases of food to Calipat. The food will be prepared by the Calipatria Unified School District Food Services Department and served to the community over the next several days. ECESD Superintendent Jon LeDoux and CUSD Superintendent Doug Kline both noted that we are one community, regardless of the distance between us. ECESD, including our Board of Trustees, is happy that we are able to provide for others in their time of need.

ECESD is committed to our community.

Our incredible Child Nutrition Team, led by Assistant Superintendent Kristy Curry, Director Molly Diaz and Assistant Director Teddy Moreno, along with over 60 of our very best food service, warehouse, delivery, maintenance, transportation, operations and administrative personnel, all working together, served 51,898 meals today in a two hour period. Ensuring our students have nutritious meals is a top priority, which is why we now serve 7 days of meals - both breakfast and lunch, every Monday. (photos courtesy of Trustee Chuck Fisher)

On this Peace Officers Memorial Day, we commend the brave men and women of our law enforcement community for continually summoning the courage to fulfill their solemn oath to protect and serve. We also pause to remember all those who have lost their lives and who have suffered permanent disabilities defending their communities and the rule of law, including the heroes we have lost this year to the coronavirus.

Thank you for everything you do!

FRAUD ALERT!!!

Be extra cautious. Unfortunately, scams and falsehoods seem to increase during urgent times.
shared_text:
County of Imperial
May 11 at 3:02 PM ·

FRAUD ALERT!!! A fraudulent letter from the Department of Social Services is being distributed advising clients that they must be tested for COVID-19 to be eligible for benefits and if found positive, children will be removed from the home and placed in foster care. THIS IS A FRAUD!! State Departments and county human services departments will NEVER ask about health status in connection to an application for benefits and children cannot be put into foster care just because a parent may be ill. If you receive this letter, please DO NOT respond.

Since yesterday afternoon some have been unable to access the district homepage (www.ecesd.org). A message appears warning that the site is either “not private” or “not secure.”

This issue is affecting several websites worldwide. For the time being, please bypass the message. Accessing www.ecesd.org is completely SAFE.

The bypass instructions vary by device and by Internet browser. The general instructions are to, 1) Select Advanced or Show Details, 2) Click Proceed to www.ecesd.org, or click ‘visit this website.’

Typically, we would NOT recommend bypassing this message. However, in this particular case, bypassing the warning is completely safe. For the safety of your computer and files, do not bypass other websites unless instructed to do so.

This message is a reminder that all the schools and offices are currently closed due to the COVID-19 Pandemic and will remain closed until the end of the school year or until the Governor lifts the shelter in place order. This week we are on Spring Break, but starting next Monday, April 20th, although our facilities will be closed, learning will still be happening through distance learning. Please go to the district website at www.ecesd.org or this Facebook page to stay informed.
----------------------------------------
Este mensaje es un recordatorio de que todas las escuelas y oficinas están actualmente cerradas debido a la pandemia COVID-19 y permanecerán cerradas hasta el final del año escolar o hasta que el gobernador levante la orden de refugio en hogar. Esta semana estamos en vacaciones de primavera, pero a partir del próximo lunes 20 de abril, aunque nuestras instalaciones estarán cerradas, el aprendizaje seguirá ocurriendo a través de la educación a distancia. Visite nuestro sitio web www.ecesd.org o esta pagina de Facebook para mantenerte informado.

Starting Monday, April 6th, we are going to single day serving of meals. We will distribute enough food for 5 days every MONDAY between 11:00 am to 1:00 pm. By regulation you may only receive one breakfast and one lunch per child per day, this includes food services at other school districts.
---------------------------
A partir del lunes 6 de abril, vamos a servir comidas un solo día. Distribuiremos suficiente comida durante 5 días todos los LUNES entre las 11:00 a.m. y la 1:00 p.m. Por reglamento, solo puede recibir un desayuno y un almuerzo por niño por día, esto incluye servicios de alimentos en otros distritos escolares.

post_text:
Congratulations to our very own Superintendent Jon LeDoux on being named the 2020 San Diego and Imperial Counties’ Superintendent of the Year by the Association of California School Administrators!

When asked about the award, Mr. LeDoux stated that it is not really about him, but about the great work the staff at ECESD has performed over the years. He elaborated by saying, “I have had a very supportive school board over the years that has allowed me to assemble the best staff in the county – from our district administrative team to our principals, teachers and support staff – everyone is committed to the mission of ensuring our students receive the best education, day in and day out. When everyone is working together, great things happen. This award is merely a reflection on our common mission, and I am truly grateful to be able to accept it on behalf of our 700+ employees who give their all to our community and schools.”

Harding School hosted VERY special guests as George and Audrey McFaddin dropped by McFaddin Hall to view the newly installed dedication plaques in George's honor.

Mr. McFaddin then visited Mrs. Worsley's class in McFaddin Hall where students were introduced to this very special man. They were in awe to meet a man who had a building named after him.

George promised to stop by every now and then to visit students in his namesake building.

Mr. McFaddin is ALWAYS welcome at every school in the ECESD.

post_text:
Public asked to help name new school!

Though construction on the planned school is not expected to get underway for about two years, district officials are hoping to select a name for the campus in the coming months.

Community members can submit a recommended name and a short reason why they feel the district should adopt the suggested name via email to the district's Naming Committee at newschool@ecesd.org or via mail at Naming Committee, El Centro Elementary School District, 1256 Broadway, El Centro, CA 92243

Detailed information can be found in today's front page of the Imperial Valley Press

post_text:
NOTICE CALLING FOR PROPOSALS

The El Centro Elementary School District, hereafter called, District, will receive electronic proposals for the following services: RFP No. 2020-01 - Classroom Projector Project Proposals, to be received no later than 12:00 pm on Wednesday, June 19, 2019, via email. A mandatory conference and site-walk will take place on Thursday, June 13, 2019, starting at 9:00 am at the following location: 2370 W. Main Street, El Centro, CA 92243. Contractors not attending the conference or arriving after 9:00 am will be disqualified. RFP documents are available for download at www.ecesd.org/technology, under the section ‘Bids/RFPs’ or by contacting Mr. Antonio Romayor Jr at aromayor@ecesd.org. The District reserves the right to reject any or all proposals and to waive any informality or irregularity in any bid received.
